{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8120af2c-4c47-491b-94de-8a2a91a373d8","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/your/McpServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that:\n\n1. **Spawns your server** as a child process using stdio\n2. **Lists tools** — click \"Tools\" → \"List Tools\" to see registered tools\n3. **Invoke tools** — select a tool, fill in parameters, and call it\n4. **View raw JSON-RPC** — inspect request/response messages in real time\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Environment variables**: Pass them with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e MY_VAR=value dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer\n  ```\n- **Arguments after `--`**: If your server needs CLI args:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer -- --my-flag\n  ```\n- **Logging**: Any output your server writes to `stderr` appears in the Inspector's console (stdout is reserved for JSON-RPC).\n- **Attach a debugger**: Since the Inspector spawns `dotnet run`, you can attach your IDE debugger to the child process, or add `Debugger.Launch()` in development builds.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9df13330-cc2d-445e-bc70-47f5bf3016d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"C404:1E89:CFD1B3:E3A71A:69FBB47A"},"id":"1e7713cb-6173-4a64-b378-1d8374131842","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:37:09.162Z","parentId":"216dd94e-cbd9-4567-8a68-20399fa17ad4"}
